Here's the registration and the reasoning:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // HttpClient: singleton so one instance manages connection pooling app-wide.
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();

        // DataService: singleton because it wraps HttpClient, holds no
        // per-user state, and should be reused to avoid redundant allocations.
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels: transient so each navigation gets fresh state.
        // Avoids stale data when navigating back and forth.
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages: transient to match their ViewModels — each navigation
        // push creates a new page with a new VM injected.
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | Singleton | One instance reuses TCP connections efficiently; avoids socket exhaustion |
| `IDataService` | Singleton | Stateless API wrapper — safe to share, expensive to recreate |
| ViewModels | Transient | Each navigation needs fresh state; singletons would show stale data |
| Pages | Transient | Pages bind to their ViewModel — must match the VM lifetime |

**When to use Scoped instead:** If you later adopt `Shell`-based navigation with route parameters, consider `AddScoped` for ViewModels so state lives for the duration of a navigation scope rather than being instantly disposable. In most MAUI apps without well-defined scopes, transient is the safer default.
